result.execSummary:
The defendant Jessica Aa Dykeman was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Forgery-Writings or Objects, a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.38(1)(a).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Case called at 9:48 am [Clerk SH]
Defendant Jessica Aa Dykeman in court with Attorney Yelena Olegovna Zarwell. DA Susan V. Happ appeared for the State of Wisconsin.

Court examines the Defendant as to rights, understanding & intent.  
Ms. Dykeman waives her right to Preliminary Hearing; the Court accepts this waiver and binds her over for Arraignment.
State files information; Arraignment--service of Information admitted, reading waived
On Motion of the State, the Court amends information to include "on or about" language in Count #1

Constitutional rights given; plea of "No Contest" entered on Count #1; factual basis stipulated; victim rights compliance verified; Court finds the plea has been entered freely, voluntarily, intelligently and accepts the plea, finds Defendant guilty, and orders JOC entered.
On Motion of the State, the Court reads-in and dismisses Count #2

On Count #1, the Court withholds sentence, places Defendant on Probation for 3 years, with conditions:
--serve 120 days in Jefferson County Jail, with Huber/Work-release privileges for purposes of education, child care and employment; to commence 7/19/14 at 12:00 pm. Sentence may transfer to Waukesha County as long as electronic monitoring is not utilized.
--Defendant is required to report for commencement and service of jail sentence with absolute sobriety and without controlled substances in system; non-compliance will result in loss of Huber privileges without further process.
--To undergo any assessment, treatment or counseling as required per Agent
--To pursue employment and/or education program or combination of the two, per Agent
--No contact with John or Merry Kohn
--To pay costs of $268
--To submit DNA Sample upon demand
--To pay $250 DNA Surcharge
